(1) CHARACTERS. —In this scene Theopropides, who had been to Egypt to improve his fortunes, is introduced, attended by two mute porters. He is a typical father of Graeco-Roman comedy in being stupid and having a moral code that asked economy of his son and nothing more (cf. 1160 ᾗ). His most individual trait is his tiffldity, resulting from his superstition (see notes on Personae).
